Since we believe that the electrochemical properties of the samples are related to the presence of alcoholic hydroxyl groups and doped N atoms, so we study the surface chemistry of GO, PRG and APRGs in detail using XPS (Fig. 2
                         and Table 2
                        ). As shown in Fig. 2a, the XPS full spectra of all samples exhibit that the intensities of the O1s peaks are diminished and the C1s peaks are increased from GO to PRG and APRGs, indicating the partial reduction of GO. Furthermore, there are some weak N 1s peaks in the curves of APRGs owing to the small dosage of THAM, which demonstrates the N doping of GO. The C1s spectrum of APRG-30 (Fig. 2b) can be decomposed into five peaks at 284.77, 285.36, 286.31, 287.39 and 288.98 eV, which respectively assigned to C=C/C-C, C-OH, C=N/C-O, C-N/C=O and O-C=O. The presence of C=N and C-N peaks further confirms the successfully doped of N atoms in graphene sheets. Furthermore, the high-resolution N1s spectrum of APRG-30 (Fig. 2c) can be resolved into three peaks ascribing to pyridinic N (399.42 eV), pyrrolic N (400.90 eV) and graphitic N (402.49 eV), respectively. Related studies have shown that the capacitance properties of N-doped graphene are closely related to its doping configurations, because they can yield pseudocapacitance effect and improve the conductivity of carbon materials [32,33]. The pyridinic N refers to the configuration where N atoms replace the location of carbon atoms in hexatomic rings, and pyrrolic N indicates the N atoms in five-membered rings. Both pyridinic N and pyrrolic N are located at the periphery or the defect sites, while the graphitic N implies the N substituting carbon atom in graphene plane [27]. Graphitic N and pyridinic N have a large dipole moment, which can improve the wettability of the materials. In addition, graphitic N can promote electron transfer, thereby improving the capacitance performance of electrode materials by reducing the charge transfer resistance [34,35]. Moreover, pyridinic N and pyrrolic N have electrochemical activity in alkaline aqueous solution, so they can generate pseudocapacitance [36].
